{
  "doc_id": "55615",
  "text": "A choledochal cyst is a cystic dilatation of the biliary tree and a well-known cause of biliary tract malignancies. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] It is a relatively rare disease; incidence rates ranging from 0.32% in Asia and 1 in 13,000 to 1 in 2 million births in western countries. [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] Most cases are diagnosed during early childhood, but between 20% to 30% of cases are first detected in adults as choledochal cyst either causing symptoms or found incidentally during imaging for an unrelated cause. [CITATION_6] It has been reported that only a small number of patients who underwent surgical management for choledochal cyst had progression to biliary malignancy. [CITATION_7] The incidence of cancer in patients with primary choledochal cyst is 9.9%, whereas the incidence of cancer development after cyst excision is 0.6%. [CITATION_8] Herein, we present a case of a patient who had been treated for choledochal cyst in an alternative manner with no follow-up, which then progressed to cholangiocarcinoma. ",
